Ep. 4: period pain😣🤦‍♀️[i gotchu💌⤵️] I’m Chee Hee, a Chinese Medicine student and I’m graduating this year! Before that, I want to take you on this journey with me and learn different acupuncture points in your body that you can massage yourself for specific conditions 💛 so join me and follow along for more. In this fourth episode, I introduced the acupuncture point SanYinJiao (SP6), a favorite point for period pain(dysmenorrhea/menstrual cramps). Reports on the incidence of primary dysmenorrhea vary considerably, ranging from 20% to up to 90% of menstruating females. So share this to your friends. You never know who might need this💛 Acupressure is a traditional Chinese healing technique that involves applying pressure to specific points on the body to promote relaxation, relieve pain, and [improve overall healt](https://www.healthfab.in/blogs/lifestyle/ways-to-improve-mental-health-during-periods)h. SP6, also known as Sanyinjiao, is another effective acupressure point for relieving period pain. It is located on the inner side of the calf, three finger widths above the ankle bone and between the two tendons. Sanyinjiao is known to regulate the menstrual cycle and is often used to relieve menstrual cramps, lower back pain, and irregular periods. Massage gently in small circles. Do this for 1-3 minutes. You can do it yourself or do it for someone else. You should have a deep aching feeling and a feeling of relaxation and relief. Let me know if it works 🥰 Note: Do not use SP6 during pregnancy! When there was period problems such as dysmenorrhea, or unusual color and cycle of menstruation, it has the best therapeutic effect when massaging Sanyinjiao point a week before the menstrual period. Evidence Based Study: There are many articles published about this acupuncture point and I think this is one that’s pretty interesting: “Effect of acupressure at the Sanyinjiao point on primary dysmenorrhea: A randomized controlled trial” https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S1744388110000319 #tcm #periodpain #painrelief #menstrualcramps

Water droplet Bouncing due to surface tension ✨✨ Water that falls onto such a surface usually partially or completely bounces off. On impact, the droplet first spreads out like a pancake, but then retracts towards its centre, pulled together by surface tension — the force that compels all droplets form a perfect sphere. This process is known as a coalescence cascade. The droplet will hit the surface, partially coalesce with the bulk, re-emerge as a smaller droplet, bounce 1-3 times, partially coalesce again, re-emerge again as an even smaller droplet and so on. 🎥: dm for credits Follow -@factulicious for more auch stuff #science #physics #surfacetension #water #jee #drops #trending #fyp
